  "prompt": "Do all jobs in science require chemistry and physics? What if I just like biology?",
  "response": "Not all science jobs require extensive chemistry and physics knowledge. Many careers focus primarily on biology, such as:\n\n1. Biology-focused careers:\n- Zoologist\n- Marine biologist\n- Wildlife biologist\n- Ecologist\n- Conservation scientist\n- Genetics researcher\n- Microbiologist\n- Biodiversity specialist\n\n2. Health-related biology careers:\n- Medical researcher\n- Physician\n- Veterinarian\n- Biotechnologist\n- Epidemiologist\n- Pharmacologist\n\n3. Environmental biology careers:\n- Environmental scientist\n- Park ranger\n- Forest ranger\n- Nature conservation officer\n\nWhile some basic chemistry and physics knowledge can be helpful, many of these careers emphasize biological sciences. However, depending on the specific role or advanced research positions, some understanding of chemistry and physics might still be beneficial.\n\nIf you're passionate about biology, you can definitely find careers that focus primarily on biological sciences without requiring deep expertise in chemistry or physics.\n\nWould you like to explore some of these biology-related career paths in more detail?",
